# Pipeline Architecture

## Dependency Direction

`gui → pipeline` only. Pipeline packages (`ingestion`, `ocr`, `extraction`, `validation`, `report`) must never import from `src/gui/`. The GUI is a thin presentation layer over the pipeline.

## Classification Placeholder

`src/classification/` is a structural placeholder. **Do not add logic to it until explicitly instructed.** The beta assumes all input documents are valid income documents — classification is skipped entirely. When classification is ready, it will slot between OCR and Extraction without changing either stage.

## Report vs. Extraction

`src/report/` consumes cached extraction results and produces output artifacts. It must not perform field extraction. Extraction produces data; report assembly consumes it. Keep these concerns separate.

## Stage Contracts

Each stage has a defined contract:

- **Preconditions** — what the stage expects as input (e.g., OCR expects an image or PDF path)
- **Postconditions** — what the stage guarantees as output (e.g., extraction returns a typed dataclass or raises)
- **Invariants** — what always holds (e.g., every extracted value carries `source_document` and `source_location`)

Keep contracts narrow (ISP). A caller that only needs extracted text should not depend on a type that also carries bounding boxes and confidence scores. Split contracts when consumers only need a subset.

## Open/Closed Principle

New stages slot in without editing existing ones. Write stages that consume a well-defined input and produce a well-defined output so new stages can be inserted around them.

## Traceability

Every extracted value must carry provenance. This is a hard requirement.

```python
@dataclass
class ExtractedField:
    name: str
    value: str
    source_document: str
    source_location: str | None = None
    confidence: float | None = None
```

Never return a bare value from an extraction function when a traced dataclass is expected.
